Clean code

--code is the language in which we ultimately express the requirements.

--"Bad code tempts the mess to grow ".

--productivity of the code is inversely proportional to mess.

--spending time keeping your code clean is not just cost effective, it’s a matter of professional survival.

--writing a bad code means you are unprofessional.

--clean code is pleasing to read,it’s left by someone who cares deeply about the craft.

--Clean code should be elegant ,efficient ,simple ,direct and small better than large.

--It runs all the tests,has  no duplication ,includes meaningful names and minimizes the number of entities.

--It has unit and acceptance tests. It has meaningful names and provides a clear and minimal API

--we can  change one variable name for the better, break up one function that’s a little too large, eliminate one small bit of duplication, clean up one composite if statement.
